result.execSummary:
The defendant Nathan B Kohls was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

4:22 pm Def in court w/ Atty Elizabeth Ann Wright.  Def in custody.  John William Kellis appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Plea Questionnaire filed - signed/understands.  No threat/force.  

14CF-418:  Count 1 - Fleeing an Officer as a Repeater (Misd)  GUILTY.  Count 2 - Possession of Controlled Substances as a Repeater (Misd)  GUILTY.  Count 3 - Possession of THC as a Repeater (Misd)  GUILTY.  Count 4 - Dismissee but read-in.
14CF-451:  Count 1 - Misd Bail Jumping (new crime) as a Repeater)  GUILTY.  Count 2 - Obstructing an Officer as a Repeater (Misd)  GUILTY.

COURT is satisfied that the pleas are F, I & V made.  Sufficient factual basis.  Found guilty and convicted.
Kellis recommends probation with em.  He just turned 23 and has 23 convictions as a repeater in a short period of time.  If he gets revoked, he'll get a significant sentence...   Wright comments.  He states he might have trouble doing probation so he asks that you max it out.  He'd like to do community service.  He's done CS in the past and it was not court ordered.  He does it because he likes it.  He's grateful that he's not getting felony convictions.  Kohls comments.  Court comments.

SENTENCES:  1 year CJ on each count - concurrent w/ 14 days credit - 30 days to report and then he can do em if he finds a place to be able to do em.  All  CC reduced to a civil judgment.
